[[File:Nubuk.JPG|right|thumb|275px|A nubuck shoe]] '''Nubuck''' (pronounced {{IPAc-en|ˈ|nj|uː|b|ʌ|k|}}) is top-grain cattle [[leather]] that has been sanded or buffed on the grain side, or outside, to give a slight nap of short protein fibers, producing a velvet-like surface. It is resistant to wear, and may be white or coloured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiwicare.com/US/FAQ/ |title=FAQ |publisher=Kiwicare.com |date=2011-04-08 |accessdate=2013-01-23}}</ref>
Nubuck is similar to [[suede]], but is created from the outer side of a hide, giving it more strength and thickness and a fine grain.<ref>{{cite web|author=ken@thestrapshop.co.uk |url=http://www.watchworx.co.uk/pages/glossary.html |title=Glossary of leather types and finishes. Military, Vinatage and Classic Watch Straps |publisher=Watchworx.co.uk |accessdate=2013-01-23}}</ref> It is generally more expensive than suede, and must be coloured or dyed heavily to cover up the sanding and stamping process.
Nubuck characteristics are similar to [[aniline leather]]. It is soft to the touch, scratches easily, and water drops darken it temporarily (it dries to its original color).<ref>[http://www.hihut.com/caring-for-leather-upholstery.html Caring For Leather Upholstery] - Wayne Jordan</ref>
The word nubuck probably comes from ''new'' + ''[[Buckskin (leather)|buck(skin)]]''.<ref>Merriam-Webster, [http://www.m-w.com/dictionary/nubuck nubuck], [[Oxford English Dictionary]] [http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/246270 nubuck]</ref>
