[[File:Pittsburgh toilet.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A Pittsburgh toilet.]]
A '''Pittsburgh toilet''', often called a "Pittsburgh potty", is a common fixture in pre-[[World War II]] houses built in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]. It consists of an ordinary [[flush toilet]] installed in the basement, with no surrounding walls. Most of these toilets are paired with a crude basement shower apparatus and large sink, which often doubles as a laundry basin. Also, because western Pennsylvania is a steep topographical zone, many basements have their own entryway, allowing homeowners to enter from their yard or garage, cleanse themselves in their basement, and then ascend their basement stairs refreshed.  

== Origin ==
As Pittsburgh was historically an industrial town, toilets such as these were said to be used by steelworkers and miners: grimy from the day's labor, they could use an exterior door to enter the basement directly from outside and use the basement's shower and toilet before heading upstairs.<ref>{{cite news | last =Kirkland  | first =Kevin | title =Homes & real estate: For house hunters, old and new homes each have their advantages | newspaper =[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] | date =May 22, 2004  | url =http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/sectionfront/life/homes-real-estate-for-house-hunters-old-and-new-homes-each-have-their-advantages-537760/ | accessdate =November 28, 2012  | quote=transplants [to Pittsburgh] to the area might be pleasantly surprised by a few aspects of Pittsburgh housing stock. No, we're not talking about the Pittsburgh toilet, the ubiquitous basement fixture that harkens back to the heyday of the steel mills and coal mines. Not usually a big selling point, it nevertheless provides a good starting point for a basement powder room.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Billingsly | first =Sarah | title =Eclectic Pittsburgh Architecture reflects Industrial Influence
 | newspaper =[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] | date =September 24, 2003 | url =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lIlIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hnADAAAAIBAJ&pg=4197,3781396| page=EG-6 | accessdate =November 28, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title =‘You Wanted To Know’: Pittsburgh Potty Origins | newspaper =[[KDKA-TV]] | date =September 17, 2012  | url =http://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2012/09/17/you-wanted-to-know-pittsburgh-potty-origins/ | accessdate = November 28, 2012}}</ref> This usage is largely unverified by historians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wesa.fm/post/documenting-pittsburgh-potty-architectural-mystery-our-basements|title=Documenting The Pittsburgh Potty: An Architectural Mystery In Our Basements|last=Kovash|first=Sarah|access-date=2017-10-12|language=en}}</ref> The Pittsburgh toilet may have been used to divert sewer backups out of the living space of the house. The toilet in the basement would overflow from the sewer backup because it is the lowest point in the system, and the mess would be relatively easy to clean compared to an upstairs bathroom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wesa.fm/post/architect-offers-explanation-pittsburgh-s-basement-toilets-and-it-s-not-what-you-think|title=Architect Offers Explanation For Pittsburgh’s Basement Toilets (And It’s Not What You Think)|last=Kovash|first=Sarah|access-date=2017-10-12|language=en}}</ref>  {{Portal|Pittsburgh}}

