}</ref> Construction on the dam began in June 1998 but stalled in 2008. [[Impregilo|Salini Impregilo]] began to finish the dam in 2011. Heavy flooding in February 2014 caused a partial [[slope failure|failure]] on 4 February, on the downstream face of the dam.<ref>{{cite web |title=Water gushes over crumbling dam wall in Zimbabwe|url=http://digitaljournal.com/news/environment/water-gushes-over-crumbling-dam-wall-in-zimbabwe/article/369683 |publisher=Digital Journal|accessdate=25 February 2014|date=9 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tokwe - Mukorsi Dam|url=http://www.salini-impregilo.com/en/projects/in-progress/dams-hydroelectric-plants-hydraulic-works/tokwe-mukorsi-dam.html |publisher=Salini Impregilo|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref> By late February the dam had not been fully breached but the unplanned rising reservoir behind the dam caused evacuations upstream.<ref>{{cite web |title=Update: Tokwe Mukorsi dam in Zimbabwe |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/environment/update-tokwe-mukorsi-dam-in-zimbabwe/article/372939 |publisher=Digital Journal|accessdate=25 February 2014 |date=25 February 2014}}</ref> Both upstream and downstream, over 20,000 people were evacuated.<ref>{{cite web|title=In photos: The aftermath of Zimbabwe’s Tokwe-Mukorsi dam disaster|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-04-14-in-photos-the-aftermath-of-zimbabwes-tokwe-mukorsi-dam-disaster/#.VKVoZivF-So|publisher=Daily Maverick|accessdate=1 January 2015|date=14 April 2014}}</ref> Construction of the dam was suspended in June 2014 due to a lack of funding.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tokwe-Mukorsi construction suspended |url=https://www.newsday.co.zw/2014/06/26/tokwe-mukorsi-construction-suspended/ |publisher=News Day |accessdate=1 January 2015|date=26 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tokwe Mukosi dam complete|url=http://www.thezimbabwean.co/news/zimbabwe-news/74430/tokwe-mukosi-dam-complete.html|accessdate=17 January 2015|agency=The Zimbabwean|date=7 January 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150119004839/http://www.thezimbabwean.co/news/zimbabwe-news/74430/tokwe-mukosi-dam-complete.html|archivedate=19 January 2015|df=}}</ref> The power station was expected to be commissioned by the end of 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zimbabwe: IDBZ to Issue U.S$65 Million Bonds for Power Projects |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201411180280.html |accessdate=17 January 2015 |agency=The Herald|publisher=All Africa |date=18 November 2014}}</ref> It is {{Convert|90.3|m}} tall and creates a {{Convert|1750000000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}} reservoir, the largest the in country. The associated [[hydroelectric]] power station will have a {{convert|12|MW}} installed capacity.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cheap design linked to problems at Tokwe-Mukosi |url=http://nehandaradio.com/2014/02/15/cheap-design-linked-problems-tokwe-mukosi/ |publisher=Nehanda Radio |accessdate=25 February 2014|date=15 February 2014}}</ref>
In May 2016 the government released $35 million to Salini Impregilio to enable the Italian contractor resume construction work that stopped two years ago owing to payment problems. <ref>[http://www.zimbabwesituation.com/news/zimsit-m-tokwe-mukosi-dam-contractor-resumes-work-the-herald/ Tokwe-Mukosi Dam contractor resumes work]</ref> The Dam was eventually completed in December 2016 and commissioned in May 2017
